The decision to graduate in two years was practical: with my sister entering college, I felt a sense of responsibility to graduate early and ease my family's financial burden. Motivated to act quickly, I began conducting research as a freshman, started an algorithms club, and sought out mentors. This pressure taught me to identify opportunities and be manage long-term time constraints. It shaped me as a student and learner, and given me the resourcefulness and commitment to succeed in grad school.

Making an effort to engage in leadership as an undergrad helped me experience diverse perspectives. I felt that undergraduate students were limited in the depth they could explore within algorithms, and so I started an algorithm club. By reaching out to students from various departments, I attracted people from diverse academic backgrounds in mathematics, economics, computer science, and engineering disciplines to the club. As a result of this diversity, newer students often helped guide interesting discussions in directions I did not expect. In one such meeting, a younger student's questions on minimum cuts led to a discussion on submodularity. When discussing fair division, economics students were able to provide a perspective on the differences between traditional economics and economics in computation. These moments taught me the value of diversity in finding different approaches to problems and asking new questions. In the Multimodal Interactions Lab, the same was true. When I introduced new students to human-computer interaction literature, their perspectives led to insightful research discussions on potential applications of the results in the papers and improved approaches.

Such discussions gave me insight into my own work as well. Finding communities with different research interests and taking courses such as combinatorial optimization helped me better appreciate how my work in fair division connected with other parts of theoretical computer science. As a graduate student, I'm eager to continue working with people across subdisciplines within theoretical computer science, to mentor students encountering new research areas, and to help create inclusive problem-solving communities. 
